---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonical={canonical}
  ogType="article"
  ogImage={ogImage}
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(articleJsonLd)} />
    <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbJsonLd)} />
    <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(organizationJsonLd)} />
  </Fragment>

  <div class="pl-page">

    {/* HERO */}
    <section class="pl-hero" data-screen-label="01 Hero">
      <div class="pl-hero-grid"></div>
      <div class="pl-hero-bg"></div>
      <div class="pl-hero-eyebrow">Profit Leaks &middot; A Pillar</div>
      <h1 id="hero-headline">The Profit Leaks<br/>Hiding in Every Firm.</h1>
      <p class="pl-hero-sub" id="hero-sub">
        Most professional service firms in the <strong>$5M to $50M range</strong> are losing margin to operational friction they have not yet quantified. The standard month-end close will not surface it. It is not designed to. Here is what a forensic look actually finds.
      </p>
      <div class="pl-hero-cta">
        <a href="/get-started" class="pl-btn" id="hero-cta">Start Your Diagnostic <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span></a>
        <a href="/go/five-profit-leaks" class="pl-btn is-ghost">Download the Field Guide <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span></a>
      </div>
      <span class="pl-nda">A mutual confidentiality agreement (NDA) is executed prior to any data intake.</span>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 2: THE FEELING */}
    <section class="pl-section" data-screen-label="02 The Feeling">
      <div class="pl-inner pl-narrow">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">02 &middot; The Feeling</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">You Already Know <span class="roman">Something</span> Is Off.</h2>
        <div class="pl-body">
          <p>If you are running a professional service firm and revenue is growing but profit does not feel like it is keeping pace, you are not imagining it.</p>
          <p>We keep hearing the same thing from managing partners in your range. Revenue is up 15, 20, sometimes 30 percent year over year. The team is bigger. The pipeline is full. But the cash in the bank at the end of the quarter does not feel right. Something is leaking, and the P&amp;L is not telling you where.</p>
          <p><em>Do you feel that too?</em></p>
          <p>If you do, the instinct is almost always right. You need to trust your gut. The reason the standard financial reporting cannot surface this is not because the data is missing. It is because the standard close is built to record what happened, not explain why. Finding the leak requires a different kind of look.</p>
          <p>That is what this page is. A walkthrough of the categories where we keep finding recoverable profit, the single structural reason they all exist, and an illustrative sample diagnostic that shows what a finished engagement looks like.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-root-box">
          <div class="kicker">The short version</div>
          <p class="pull">Three leaks lead, two are fast wins we pick up along the way, and one sits underneath where receivables come up. None of them are exotic. They're the ordinary ones that accumulate quietly while everyone's focused on the next client.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 3: ROOT CAUSE */}
    <section class="pl-section" data-screen-label="03 Root Cause" style="background: var(--pl-white);">
      <div class="pl-inner pl-narrow">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">03 &middot; The Root Cause</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">Growth Without <span class="roman">Infrastructure.</span></h2>
        <div class="pl-body">
          <p>The reason profit leaks are so hard to see is that they are not really separate problems. They are symptoms of one structural condition.</p>
          <p>Here is the pattern we keep seeing in firms your size. The firm grew. Revenue doubled, maybe tripled, over five to seven years. The team grew. Offices opened. Services expanded. Sometimes there were acquisitions. But the management infrastructure (pricing governance, vendor oversight, financial reporting, accountability for output) did not scale at the same pace.</p>
          <p>What that leaves is a firm that operates on autopilot in places it used to operate on judgment. Division managers set their own prices. Departments contract their own vendors. Subscriptions renew without review. Headcount grows faster than the revenue it produces. The founder is still running on instincts that worked at $5M, but the firm is at $25M or $40M now, and the gap between operational complexity and management infrastructure is where the margin escapes.</p>
          <p>Every category below is a version of this same story. Price leakage is really "no centralized rate governance." Vendor leakage is really "no centralized procurement." Labor leakage is really "no line of sight from headcount to the revenue it produces." When we run a diagnostic, we are not so much finding isolated problems as mapping the places the same infrastructure gap shows up.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-root-box">
          <div class="kicker">The Reframe</div>
          <p class="pull">You cannot fix a handful of separate problems simultaneously. But you can close the infrastructure gap, and the leaks close behind it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 4: THE LEAKS */}
    <section class="pl-section" data-screen-label="04 The Leaks">
      <div class="pl-inner">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">04 &middot; The Leaks</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">Where <span class="roman">the Money</span> Hides.</h2>
        <p class="pl-body" style="max-width: 60rem;">
          These categories come from real diagnostic work across professional service firms. They are not theoretical. They are the patterns we keep seeing, and they fall into three tiers: <strong>three that lead</strong>, <strong>two fast wins</strong> we pick up along the way, and <strong>one secondary</strong> that surfaces where receivables come up.
        </p>

        <div class="pl-leaks">

          {/* Tier A: Headline leaks */}
          <div class="pl-subcat-head">
            <span class="tag">4A &middot; The Headline Three</span>
            <h3>The Leaks That Lead.</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="pl-subcat-intro">
            These three carry the most margin and they are where almost every diagnostic spends its time: the gap between the price you set and the price you collect, the work you have earned that never gets invoiced, and the payroll that has drifted out of step with the revenue it produces.
          </p>

          {/* Leak 1: Price Leakage */}
          <div class="pl-leak" id="leak-price">
            <div class="pl-leak-head">
              <h4><span class="num">01</span>Price Leakage</h4>
              <div class="pl-leak-tag">The rate you set isn't the rate you collect.</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="pl-leak-body">
                <p>The price you set and the price you actually collect aren't the same number. Discounts that quietly became defaults, rates that never got reset at renewal, escalators nobody applied, margin handed back one approval at a time.</p>
                <p>None of it looks like a problem in the moment. Each concession made sense for the deal in front of you. But they don't reverse on their own. The cost to deliver climbs while the price holds, and a few years in the gap between your rate card and your realized rate is usually the single largest leak we find. The revenue line still looks healthy, which is exactly why the erosion stays invisible.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="pl-action">
                <div class="kicker">One thing you can do</div>
                <p class="txt">Pick your three longest-running client engagements. Calculate the actual fully-loaded delivery cost (not just direct labor, include allocated overhead). Compare it to what you are billing. The gap is the leak.</p>
              </div>

              <MarginErosionChart client:visible />
            </div>
          </div>

          {/* Leak 2: Billing Leakage */}
          <div class="pl-leak" id="leak-billing">
            <div class="pl-leak-head">
              <h4><span class="num">02</span>Billing Leakage</h4>
              <div class="pl-leak-tag">Earned work that never becomes an invoice.</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="pl-leak-body">
                <p>Work you've already earned that never turns into an invoice. Time that doesn't get captured, scope that creeps in unbilled, jobs that close before the billing catches up to them.</p>
                <p>This one hurts twice. The revenue never lands, and because it was never recorded, it doesn't even show up as a loss. It's simply absent from the P&amp;L, which is why it can run for years without anyone naming it. Usually it's a gap between work-complete and invoice-sent that nobody owns, plus an approval or two sitting in an inbox while the invoice waits behind it.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="pl-action">
                <div class="kicker">One thing you can do</div>
                <p class="txt">Ask your billing team for the average number of days between work-complete and invoice-sent, and the dollar value of billable time written down last quarter. If nobody can answer quickly, that gap is the leak.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          {/* Leak 3: Labor Leakage */}
          <div class="pl-leak" id="leak-labor">
            <div class="pl-leak-head">
              <h4><span class="num">03</span>Labor Leakage</h4>
              <div class="pl-leak-tag">Labor cost drifting out of step with revenue.</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="pl-leak-body">
                <p>Labor cost drifting out of step with the revenue it produces. People you're paying for who aren't billing, utilization sliding without anyone clocking it, senior people doing work that should sit lower.</p>
                <p>It's the leak managing partners feel before they can name it. The team grew, payroll grew faster, and revenue per person quietly slid. Firms hire ahead of demand, which is often the right call. The leak isn't the hire; it's that the projection that justified the headcount rarely gets revisited twelve months on, so the drift never gets a second look.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="pl-action">
                <div class="kicker">One thing you can do</div>
                <p class="txt">Pull total payroll cost by department or practice group, and the revenue each group produced over the same period. If you can't tie recent hires back to the revenue they were meant to produce, that's where to look first.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          {/* Tier B: Quick wins */}
          <div class="pl-subcat-head">
            <span class="tag">4B &middot; The Quick Wins</span>
            <h3>The Fast Ones.</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="pl-subcat-intro">
            These two are the low-effort wins we tend to find along the way. They don't need a strategy; they need someone to actually look. That's why they usually land in the first wave of recovery rather than the long haul.
          </p>

          {/* Leak 4: Vendor Leakage */}
          <div class="pl-leak" id="leak-vendor">
            <div class="pl-leak-head">
              <h4><span class="num">04</span>Vendor Leakage</h4>
              <div class="pl-leak-tag">Indirect spend nobody owns.</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="pl-leak-body">
                <p>Indirect and recurring spend nobody owns. A vendor list growing faster than the business, the same thing bought at five different prices, the occasional payment that slips out twice.</p>
                <p>As a firm grows, departments and offices start contracting on their own. Procurement is informal, approvals happen over email, and a few years in you're paying two or three vendors for overlapping things, sometimes the same vendor under two account numbers billed to two cost centers. Each purchase made sense alone. Together they're a leak nobody decided on, and the fix is one of the fast ones.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="pl-action">
                <div class="kicker">One thing you can do this week</div>
                <p class="txt">Pull your last four months of vendor invoices and sort them by vendor name. Scan for duplicates. Most firms find at least one. Some firms find thirty.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          {/* Leak 5: Software Leakage */}
          <div class="pl-leak" id="leak-software">
            <div class="pl-leak-head">
              <h4><span class="num">05</span>Software Leakage</h4>
              <div class="pl-leak-tag">Subscriptions nobody stops to question.</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="pl-leak-body">
                <p>Subscriptions that auto-renew long after anyone's using them. Seats nobody logs into, overlapping tools three teams bought separately, renewals nobody stops to question.</p>
                <p>A tool gets adopted for a project. The project ends. The subscription renews itself. Seats stay live for people who left. Two tools end up doing the same job because different offices bought them months apart. Each line is small enough to ignore, which is exactly how the stack quietly doubles, and the cancellation list is usually shorter to build than anyone expects.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="pl-action">
                <div class="kicker">One thing you can do</div>
                <p class="txt">Export your subscription list from your accounting system. Flag anything that has not been logged into by more than two people in the last 90 days. That is your cancellation shortlist.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          {/* Tier C: Secondary */}
          <div class="pl-subcat-head">
            <span class="tag">4C &middot; Secondary</span>
            <h3>The One Underneath.</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="pl-subcat-intro">
            Not a brand pillar, but it surfaces naturally wherever receivables come up: cash you've earned that lands later than it should, costing you to wait for it.
          </p>

          {/* Leak 6: Collection Drag */}
          <div class="pl-leak" id="leak-collection">
            <div class="pl-leak-head">
              <h4><span class="num">06</span>Collection Drag</h4>
              <div class="pl-leak-tag">Earned cash that ages too long.</div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="pl-leak-body">
                <p>Cash you've earned sitting in receivables too long. It mostly pays, eventually, but in the meantime it's financing the client's business instead of yours.</p>
                <p>This isn't lost money the way the others are. It's money arriving late enough that it costs you to wait for it, drawn on the revolver and paid for in interest while it ages. Nobody's negligent; collections just isn't anyone's full-time job, so the oldest receivables quietly stretch.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="pl-action">
                <div class="kicker">One thing you can do</div>
                <p class="txt">Ask whether anyone manages DSO against a target, and whether aged receivables get escalated on a defined schedule. If the answer is no, your cash is financing someone else's business.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 5: FRAGILITY LOOP */}
    <section class="pl-section pl-loop-section" data-screen-label="05 Fragility Loop">
      <div class="pl-inner">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">05 &middot; The Fragility Loop</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">The Loop You Do Not <span class="roman">Want to Be In.</span></h2>
        <div class="pl-body pl-narrow" style="margin-left: 0;">
          <p>There is a specific sequence that happens in firms where the profit leaks have been running for a while without correction. We call it the fragility loop because each cycle tightens the next.</p>
          <p>It works like this. Margin compresses by 50 to 150 basis points over two or three years. Retained earnings do not keep up with working capital needs. The revolver gets drawn on more heavily. Interest expense rises. That interest expense further compresses the margin. And the next cycle starts with less room than the last.</p>
          <p>Most firms do not realize they are in the loop until the loop produces a covenant test. At that point it is not an operational problem anymore. It is <em>a solvency event</em>, with lenders, boards, and sometimes equity contributions from the owner required to cure a technical breach.</p>
          <p>The visual below uses illustrative starting conditions for a firm at risk of covenant breach, with margin compression and revolver dependency typical of the size and operating profile. Use them, or enter your own, and see how many cycles the math takes to reach a breach.</p>
        </div>

        <FragilityLoop client:visible />

        <div class="pl-body pl-narrow" style="margin-left: 0; margin-top: 3rem;">
          <p>If any part of this loop feels familiar, that is the reason to run a diagnostic now rather than next fiscal year. <strong>Every cycle tightens the room you have to respond.</strong></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 6: WHAT A FINISHED DIAGNOSTIC LOOKS LIKE
        The figures below live ONLY inside the clearly-labelled illustrative
        sample (DecompositionBar). The surrounding copy stays numberless. */}
    <section class="pl-section pl-decomp-section" data-screen-label="06 A Finished Diagnostic">
      <div class="pl-inner">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">06 &middot; A Finished Diagnostic</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">What a Finished <span class="roman">Diagnostic</span> Looks Like.</h2>
        <div class="pl-body pl-narrow" style="margin-left: 0;">
          <p>To show how the categories come together, the chart below is an <strong>illustrative sample</strong> — a worked example of how a finished diagnostic decomposes a firm's findings across the categories above. The numbers are fictional and for demonstration only; they are not a real engagement, and not a typical or expected result.</p>
          <p>What it does show is the shape of the work: each finding sized, sorted, and traced back to the category it came from. Hover or tap any segment to see the mechanism behind it.</p>
        </div>

        <DecompositionBar client:visible />

        <div class="pl-body pl-narrow" style="margin-left: 0; margin-top: 3rem;">
          <p>The pattern in a worked example like this is usually the same one the leadership team didn't expect: the largest recoverable findings sit in pricing, not in the obvious cost lines. Prices set years ago and never revisited. Accounts priced below the floor with no escalation to catch them.</p>
          <p>Underneath it all is visibility. When financial data runs weeks stale, margin compressions go unnoticed for quarters, pricing drift goes unchallenged, and vendor and billing decisions sit waiting. The reframe is almost always that the firm doesn't have a long list of separate problems — it has one problem showing up in a lot of places: it outgrew the operating model that got it here, and the infrastructure to run the firm it became was never built.</p>
          <p>The line we hear from managing partners working through this for the first time: <strong>"That's real money. I did not have that number."</strong></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 7: TOTAL PICTURE */}
    <section class="pl-section" data-screen-label="07 Total Picture">
      <div class="pl-inner">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">07 &middot; The Total Picture</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">Add <span class="roman">Them</span> Up.</h2>
        <p class="pl-body pl-narrow" style="margin-left: 0;">
          Every firm has a different mix. But every firm we have looked at has at least three of these categories running simultaneously. The diagnostic finds them, quantifies each one against your own data, and hands you a roadmap to recover what's recoverable. Here is what the engagement itself looks like:
        </p>

        <div class="pl-stats">
          <div class="pl-stat is-hero">
            <div class="l">What You Get</div>
            <div class="v">A roadmap</div>
            <div class="d">Every leak quantified against your own data, sequenced by impact, ready to execute.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-stat">
            <div class="l">Leak Categories</div>
            <div class="v">Six</div>
            <div class="d">Three headline leaks, two quick wins, one secondary.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-stat">
            <div class="l">Total Duration</div>
            <div class="v">14 Days</div>
            <div class="d">From data intake to delivered recovery roadmap.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-stat">
            <div class="l">Fixed Price</div>
            <div class="v">$12,500</div>
            <div class="d">No scope creep. No retainer. No ambiguity.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="pl-body" style="margin-top: 2.5rem; max-width: 60rem;">
          The math on the diagnostic is straightforward. It's a fixed fee against margin that's been leaking, quietly, for years. Every finding is quantified in dollars and traced back to your own data, so you can decide what's worth recovering with the numbers in front of you.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 8: DIAGNOSTIC PROCESS */}
    <section class="pl-section" data-screen-label="08 Diagnostic Process" style="background: var(--pl-white);">
      <div class="pl-inner">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">08 &middot; The Diagnostic Process</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">What the Diagnostic <span class="roman">Actually</span> Does.</h2>
        <p class="pl-body pl-narrow" style="margin-left: 0;">
          Make the invisible visible. Three phases over 14 days.
        </p>

        <div class="pl-phases">
          <div class="pl-phase">
            <div class="num">01</div>
            <h4>Forensic Data Integration</h4>
            <p>Secure, encrypted pipeline for your financial data. General ledger, vendor invoices, payroll records, subscription logs, client contracts, billing history. No generic surveys. A mutual NDA is executed before any data intake.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-phase">
            <div class="num">02</div>
            <h4>Leakage Diagnostics and Modeling</h4>
            <p>Your data runs through the leak categories above, cross-referenced against prior diagnostics and 25 years of operational experience. Every finding quantified to a specific dollar amount under three scenarios (conservative, moderate, aggressive).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-phase">
            <div class="num">03</div>
            <h4>Executive Recovery Roadmap</h4>
            <p>You receive an executive summary, a full diagnostic report by category, a sequenced implementation roadmap, a quantification workbook showing the math behind every finding, and an executive presentation deck for your leadership or Board.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 9: TRUST FRAME */}
    <section class="pl-section" data-screen-label="09 Trust Frame">
      <div class="pl-inner">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">09 &middot; Trust Frame</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">Led by Partners. <span class="roman">Audited by</span> You.</h2>
        <div class="pl-body pl-narrow" style="margin-left: 0;">
          <p>Every BaxterLabs engagement is led exclusively by partners with 25 years of real-world P&amp;L ownership. No junior analysts. No subcontractors. No learning on your time.</p>
          <p>The methodology is auditable end to end. Every finding includes the source data citation, the calculation methodology, and the specific line items that produced the number. You can trace any finding back to your own data. If you disagree with a finding, we walk through the math together until we agree.</p>
          <p>We use advanced analytics to find patterns across your data, but the interpretation and the calls on what to recommend come from partners who have sat in the seat and owned the P&amp;L. The analytics tell us where to look. The experience tells us what the number means.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-trust-signals">
          <div class="pl-trust-signal"><strong>Mutual NDA</strong> executed before any data intake.</div>
          <div class="pl-trust-signal"><strong>100% auditable</strong> findings with source citations.</div>
          <div class="pl-trust-signal"><strong>Led exclusively by partners</strong>, not junior staff.</div>
          <div class="pl-trust-signal"><strong>Fixed price</strong> at $12,500. No scope creep.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* SECTION 10: SELF-ASSESSMENT */}
    <section class="pl-section" data-screen-label="10 Self-Assessment CTA" id="section-assess" style="background: var(--pl-white);">
      <div class="pl-inner pl-narrow">
        <div class="pl-eyebrow"><span class="line"></span><span class="txt">10 &middot; Not Ready?</span></div>
        <h2 class="pl-h2">Not Ready for a Diagnostic? <span class="roman">Start Here.</span></h2>
        <div class="pl-body">
          <p>The Profit Leak Self-Assessment takes 10 minutes and scores your firm across the leak categories above. It will not replace a forensic diagnostic, but it will tell you which categories deserve a closer look.</p>
          <p>If the results confirm what your gut is already telling you, the diagnostic is the next step. Or read <a href="/resources/five-profit-leaks">the Profit Leaks field guide</a> first if you want the long-form version of the categories before talking to anyone.</p>
        </div>
